We recommended that management:
1. Require the City Accountant and the City GSO to cause the preparation and maintenance of PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively; and strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and the actual inventory results;
2. Initiate the immediate disposal of the unserviceable assets in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445 to avoid further deterioration;
3. Require the City Accounting Office to review and reclassify PPE items to their appropriate accounts to correct the respective PPE account balances, and make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts, including those unrecorded assets; and
4. Require the Inventory Committee to ensure the completion of physical inventory taking of all properties owned by the City Government to determine the accuracy, reliability and integrity of the PPE account balances at year-end.

We recommended that management require the City Accountant to:
1. fast track the preparation of BRS for LBP General Fund account no. 2012-1001-78 and LBP Calamity Fund account no. 2012-1002-75, and begin the preparation of BRS for DBP Time Deposit account no. 0910-029982-100 and DBP current account no. 0910-029982-030;
2. consider creating a task force to prepare Bank Reconciliation Statements, preferably headed by a Certified Public Accountant (CPA) or with accounting background, and obtain snapshots of bank accounts within a week after the end of the month if awaiting bank statements would cause undue delay in the reconciliation activities;
3. prepare the BRS every month, within ten days from receipt of the Bank Statements from authorized depository banks or upon receipt of requested bank snapshots, and submit promptly the BRS including the GL/SL of Cash in Bank – LCCA and Cash in Bank – LCTD accounts, supporting schedules for all reconciling items, bank statements/bank snapshots and used checks to COA for verification and audit, in accordance with abovementioned rules and regulations; and
4. carefully reconcile the balances per books with those per bank, giving particular attention to reconciling items that stand for so many years, in order to achieve fair presentation of the Cash in Bank balances in the financial statements.

We recommended that management:
1. require all end-user units of the LGU to prepare their respective PPMP, consolidated incorporating therein all their procurement requirements for the ensuing year;
2. ensure that the City Budget Office evaluates and reviews the PPMPs submitted to its office to ensure that the planned procurements are within the approved budget of the City LGU and in compliance with the existing rules and regulations governing budgets;
3. ensure that the BAC Secretariat consolidates the reviewed and approved PPMPs to prepare a comprehensive, workable, and realistic Annual Procurement Plan of the City LGU for completion by the members of the BAC by indicating the proper modes of procurement;
4. ensure that the requirements of GPPB Circular No. 07-2015, and DBM Circular No. Letter No. 2013-14 regarding the submission of APP to GPPB and APP-CSE to DBM-PS are both complied with; and
5. ensure that only procurements in accordance with the approved APP are undertaken in compliance with Section 7.2 of R.A. 9184 and its IRR.

We recommended that management – 2012-2016:
a. require the City Accountant to persist in the City’s drive by issuing final demand letters to all concerned accountable officers and employees to render full outstanding accounting of long outstanding cash advances;
b. enjoin all concerned officials and employees to comply with the prescribed timelines on the liquidation of cash advances, and where warranted, enforce the sanctions as maybe appropriate under the afore-cited law, rules and regulations on those who fail to liquidate their cash advances within the reglementary period;
c. instruct the City Accountant to deny clearance from money accountability to retiring, resigning and transferring personnel who still have unliquidated cash advances;
d. prepare the request for authority to write-off the unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are already deceased; and
e. strictly enforce the prohibition on the granting of additional cash advances to those with outstanding cash advances.

We recommended the following courses of action:
Require the City Accounting and City General Services Office mutually exert coordinative efforts with a view to implementing the prescribed procedures on efficient PPE management, and maintaining an effective system of control that would ensure reliability of pertinent records and reports pertaining to their acquisition, utilization, and disposal. In particular, maintain the PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively for each category of asset per fund, and conduct periodic reconciliation of their respective records to forestall possible discrepancies. Any discrepancy should be immediately investigated and properly adjusted in the books to fairly present the said account in the financial statements;
Require the City Accounting Office to review and reclassify PPE items to their appropriate accounts to correct the respective PPE account balances, and make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all assets of the City Government pursuant to Paragraph 2, Section 124 of the Manual on NGAs, Volume I, and to ensure the completion thereof to determine the accuracy, reliability and integrity of the PPE account at year-end;
Require the GSO to make a separate report of the unserviceable equipment by preparing the Inspection and Inventory Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), and to initiate the immediate disposal thereof in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445;
The City GSO update the Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment (ARE) as prescribed in Appendix 53 of the Manual on the NGAS to readily identify the Accountable Officers of acquired government property, and
Include in the budget the cost of construction of garage where all the vehicles owned by the City can be safely kept and secured from exposure to elements of weather, wear and tear and other unreasonable risks causing deterioration on serviceable assets and further reduction of salvage value, as in the case of unserviceable equipment.

We recommended that Management:
require the City Accountant to persist in the City’s drive by issuing final demand letters to all concerned accountable officers to render full accounting of long outstanding cash advances by submission of fully supported liquidation statements, and/or refund the balance of unused cash advances;
enjoin all concerned officials and employees to comply with the prescribed timelines on the liquidation of cash advances, and where warranted, enforce the sanctions as maybe appropriate under the afore-cited law, rules and regulations on those who fail to liquidate their cash advances within the reglementary period;
instruct the City Accountant to deny clearance from money accountability to retiring, resigning and transferring personnel who still have unliquidated cash advances;
prepare the request for authority to write-off the unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are already deceased; and
strictly enforce the prohibition on the granting of additional cash advances to those with outstanding cash advances.

